 Enlarge





                Jacqueline Ros, CEO and co-founder of Denver-based Revolar, a 22-employee startup that… more 

                Kathleen Lavine, Denver Business Journal            








Revolar isn’t sitting still with its debut product, which drew praise and national attention over the last year.
The Denver-based tech startup this week launched its second product in a year, debuting its $79 Revolar Instinct safety device, a smaller but more up-market and capable evolution of the original Revolar product it rolled out last spring.













 Enlarge






                            Jacqueline Ros, CEO and co-founder of Denver-based Revolar, a 22-employee startup that… more 
Kathleen Lavine, Denver Business Journal










 


Revolar hustled to meet product roll-out deadlines the company set for itself to maintain a high tempo of innovation, CEO and founder Jacqueline Ros told me.
“We’re a startup — you move fast or die,” Ros said. “You have no alternative. You’ll run out of money, or your competitors will pass you.”
The 22-employee company has a crew in San Francisco this week rolling out a crowdfunding campaign to drum up orders for the updated Revolar Instinct, and to promote its new features.
Revolar employees return to Denver for product launch party Friday at the WeWork co-working building in the Lower Highland neighborhood.
Late last year, Revolar worked with software design shop Pivotal’s Denver office to overhaul the original user interface and software design for its products. The company also used that collaboration to explore user feedback, and train and hire employees while also developing the Revolar Instinct product.
A software change




Ros first thought of creating a wearable safety device after her younger sister was assaulted as a teenager.
She co-founded Revolar with Andrea Perdomo. The pair went through a 2015 Techstars startup accelerator program in Boulder, only to turn around and go through another, retail-focused Techstars accelerator program in Minneapolis with retail giant Target Corp. (NYSE: TGT) last summer.
Its first Revolar device had been on the market less than six months, and the entrepreneurs wanted to improve on it.
The original $59 clip-on Revolar alarm, which debuted last April, lets a user send a discreet emergency message and location to the user’s chosen contacts.
Revolar distinguishes itself from other panic buttons by giving users quick options other than calling 911. A pair of clicks sends a message asking the contacts to get in touch right away, a triple click signals an emergency and to send help right away.

The company wants to empower people to quickly defuse uncomfortable, potentially dangerous situations before they become physical emergencies, Ros said.
Based on feedback from early buyers, Revolar changed its software in November to let users trigger their own mobile phone to ring, creating a diversion that might help them get out of an uncomfortable situation.
Revolar users also like using the product to quickly check in with select loved ones and friends while traveling, providing an update on their location with just a single click of the device’s button.
A Trojan horse




 


The new Revolar Instinct beeps and vibrates to confirm a check-in message has been sent, but it doesn’t sound or vibrate when the user’s multiple clicks indicate a more serious situation.
The updated device will also come with a brushed-metal clip to more easily fix the Revolar Instinct to a bag, purse or belt loop, which is an addition to the product that stemmed from users saying they didn’t always want their Revolar clipped to their clothing but did want to have it with them and accessible.
Users also asked for ability to keep track of their daily steps, Ros said, which the startup was happy to add. But Revolar Instinct isn’t a fitness wearable, and the company isn’t moving its focus off safety as the product’s primary function, Ros said
“For now, step tracking is what we consider a Trojan horse — a capability that people want and gets them in the habit of wearing it every day,” she said.
And, one day, tracking steps may help Revolar devices detect impacts and assaults that a user can’t alert someone to themselves, Ros said.
Both versions of Revolar alarms are made by contract manufacturer Celestica in Thailand to be impact resistant and waterproof.
The company will be busy in coming weeks launching the Revolar Instinct’s crowdfunded debut and raising awareness about what the devices can do. After introducing Instinct, Revolar will continue to push to make its products more useful and more attractive, Ros said.
She envisions internet-connected clothing replacing Revolar’s hardware in a few years. It would be a natural evolution for a company that aims to make products as beautiful to wear as they are functional as safety devices, she said.
“There’s something to be said about feeling confident in every way, shape and form,” Ros said.

Greg Avery covers tech, telecom, aerospace, bioscience and media for the Denver Business Journal and compiles the weekly "TechFlash" email newsletter. Phone: 303-803-9222. 












